name: ethanol production from wood | ethanol, without water, in 95% solution state, from fermentation | Cutoff, U
description:
ecoQuery: https://ecoquery.ecoinvent.org/3.10/cutoff/dataset/5170/documentation

Inventory refers to the production of 1 kg hydrated ethanol 95% (dry basis, i.e. 1.05 kg hydrated ethanol 95% wet basis), respectively 1 kWh of electricity from wood (u=80%, i.e. 55% dry matter). The multioutput-process 'wood, in distillery' delivers the co-products 'ethanol, 95% in H2O, from wood, at distillery' and 'electricity, from wood, at distillery'.

This dataset includes the transport of wood from the forest to the distillery, and the processing of wood (u=80%) to hydrated ethanol (95%) and electricity. System boundary is at the distillery. Dehydration to anhydrous ethanol is not included. Process heat and power supply is ensured by the combustion of unconverted solids.
category: C:Manufacturing/20:Manufacture of chemicals and chemical products/201:Manufacture of basic chemicals, fertilizers and nitrogen compounds, plastics/2011:Manufacture of basic chemicals

processDocumentation.timeDescription: Data from 1999 to 2006, pilot scale, near-future technology
processDocumentation.geographyDescription: Data is adapted to Swiss conditions from NREL ethanol process design from yellow poplar (1999)
processDocumentation.technologyDescription: Ethanol is produced by dilute acid pre-hydrolysis and simultaneous saccharification and co-fermentation (SSCF) of lignocellulosic biomass. Process heat and power supply is ensured by the combustion of unconverted solids. Excess electricity is exported to the power grid.
processDocumentation.dataTreatmentDescription: Direct emissions (resulting from the combustion of unconverted solids, incl. lignin) are based on the the combustion of wood chips (with emission control), according to the corresponding dry matter content, carbon content and energy content.
processDocumentation.samplingDescription: Data is adapted to Swiss conditions from NREL ethanol process design from yellow poplar, modelling by ENERS (CH)
